segments.text: February 14, Valentine's Day, sitting in the basement of the Weissenbaker building,
getting ready to interview Charlie Holland, who got here a little more than 50 years ago.
Charlie, test your mic.
Testing one, two.
Is it all right?
For someone who may not have known you in a few years to come when they're looking at this material or listening to it,
would you begin by summarizing your background and experience, where you grew up, went to school,
your experience before you got to Texas A&M?
Well, I grew up in western North Carolina, and my dad was a Baptist minister.
In fact, I started the first grade the year he finished Wake Forest.
He had been in World War I, and he decided to go down and finish up.
So we moved to Wake Forest, and about Christmas time, the twins were born,
and he took me out.
He took me out of the first grade, because he was afraid I might bring home some childhood diseases.
And then the next year after that, we moved to Mountain View,
and I was just recently at Christmas going up there looking for the place that we moved to.
It was on a dirt road out from North Wilkesboro,
and this will kind of give you the view of what things were like in those times.
And he was pastor of a little Baptist church.
There was a Baptist junior college high school, and he taught the mathematics there.
And this was back in time that the Depression was coming on us out there.
And all he got out of that year's teaching at that little junior college
was an Underwood typewriter, which I have at home.
That was all they could pay.
And I went to school.
It was a little one-room schoolhouse.
First grade in the first row, second grade in the second.
Pot-bellied stove.
Down at the bottom on old slick red hill was an outhouse.
And all the kids went to the outhouse.
And also the water was simply a barrel, just like you'd see a keg of beer.
And so Dad said, when we went there, I better put you back in the first grade,
because I'm afraid I don't want you to get behind.
So I started out in the first.
Well, in that school, you could get promoted.
All you had to do was just show you could do the second grade work.
So before that...
The year was over.
I was over in the second grade, second row.
They'd moved me to the second.
So you just changed seats.
You didn't know...
No paperwork.
Before the end of the year, I was in the third row.
Well, then we moved to Stony Point, which is about 60 miles from Charlotte.
And it's still very primitive in those days,
but it did have a consolidated school.
They bused all the kids from the county into that school.
So Dad said, well, I know you were in the third.
You were in the third grade there, but I think I'll put you back and let you do the second over.
I don't want you to get behind.
Well, they put me in that second grade, and I stayed the whole year,
because they didn't know how to get me out of it, even though I knew it.
Well, right after Christmas, we went back there and was looking for this.
We wanted to go to all the places that we'd lived.
And so we went to North Wilkesboro, and there was a bypass, and we stopped at a McDonald's.
And this Mountain View wasn't even on the map yet.
And so we went there to stop at a McDonald's.
And I saw a well-dressed lady over there.
And I went over and struck up a conversation with her.
And I asked her if she knew where Mountain View was.
She said, oh, it's just right up here.
You turn off, right up the road here.
Now, let me point out that in those years,
Wilkes County was noted to be the biggest white lightning county in the United States.
And so she said, yes.
I said, I went to school there, one-room schoolhouse, outhouse down the bottom.
And so then I went on back and sat down.
She came back over afterwards, and she told my daughter or my sister that her husband had passed away.
And she says, well, what did he do?
She says, oh, he was a bootlegger.
She says, that was the only way to make a living in those years.
She says, well, didn't the law get after him?
She said, oh, yes.
He built time five different times.
So this was kind of the.
uh area that i was i grew up in uh uh and uh at the my dad and i he was always gone a lot and so
forth and we just didn't have these father to son talks that you always have nowadays you'll hear of
like andy hardy and judge stone the closest we ever came to it was the day we were packing the
car he's getting ready to take me off to this little baptist junior college mars hill out from
nashville north carolina and it was always assumed that i'd go to college it was never even
we just didn't discuss it and i delivered papers there and i knew all the professional people in
town and they said you've got there's a lot of emphasis there on you need to you need to go to
college and make something yourself you heard that over and over again and so as we were packing the
car dad said to me he says son uh uh what are you going to study when you get here
get up there i said well dan i thought i'd study dentistry he said no son i don't think i'd do that
if i were you i don't believe you'll ever be able to keep up with your tools well see i lost his saw
and hammer so many times that uh he was just and he said why don't you just go ahead and study
engineering well that's what i did and uh so after the pre-engineering course up there mars hill i went
north carolina state and my junior year i was having breakfast and that's when pearl harbor hit
and i was in my junior year and i was in the car the day we were packing the car the germans
marched in europe which marked the beginning which is the day i started to college and then when i was
in my junior year at north carolina state the germans uh the pearl harbor occurred so i went
down and i didn't want to get drafted i wanted to finish school so what i did was they had a
program there where you could become get a direct commission even though you hadn't been in rotc they
had an rotc there and people marched around all the time and
wasn't any point in taking it because i could only do two years of it so i didn't take it
and uh but i went down and got a direct commission to go in the navy and so as soon as i finished
college i had to go in the navy and i was in the navy and on destroyers for about just nearly four
years was a tour date and the roughest duty that we had was on oklahoma we went up there with nine
destroyers in the squadron and this is where the kamikazes and for about two or three months
we were
exposed to kamikazes every day and we lost six out of our nine destroyers there were only three
of us that made it back and it was just a matter of luck we weren't that much better and we just
when they'd hit one station we'd be on another one or
the plane that was coming in at you we got it shot down well uh then after the war i thought about
going to georgia tech but it turned out that there was no housing down there so i decided to work for
georgia tech and i decided to go back to north carolina state and they had put me into a little
program that was supposed to be training the plant managers of the future well it turned out it looked
like i was going to have to work on the third shift for about 10 years 15 so i decided i'd just
go back to graduate school and went back to north carolina state and dr lindsay had taught down there
and so they gave me his name i called him and came got in touch with him and so we came out here and i began
in chemical engineering in january of 1948. that's it you came to texas in january 1948
and i promised my wife because we'd been out here on when i was on the destroyer promised her we'd
never stay in texas as soon as i got my degree we were leaving well we stayed just here describe
what was what texas a m was physically what was okay what buildings give you the whole picture um
well i have some
history with that people were in this building when i was 10 years old but i came up to the
ms dot school and said you know what we'll go back to north carolina and i thought okay well
what do i do what do i do what do i do i can't do it right i thought i was going to stay in texas
and i said well you know what i'll stay at this school you can't do it right i can't do it right
and i said well i'm going to go back to north carolina and go do it because i'm going to do it
in our national assembly and so i said yeah you know where's the mc familias any mi mc familias
where's a mc familias see you in your class and he said yeah well he's in the ms quadrillion but
he's in one of the other colleges and in the ms quadrillion he's going to go to the ms quadrillion
he was a classical type individual and he said so he called up bolt boltman's executive vice
president said get this get him a room a place to stay up there so after i'd already come here
and gotten settled uh i was over in lindsey's office one day mr bolton called up and he said
he wanted to see me boy they were just shaking over there i went over so he told me but the
amusing thing is and then he ended up saying well just go over here and oh i've forgotten boyette
go see him he's in charge of housing and that was uh what i got out of him about uh
a month or so we were down there visiting with mr lee again he said
he said well i suppose you know bolton well by now i said i'm sorry mr lee our paths haven't
crossed any since that one time i met him but uh dr lindsey was head of the uh chemical engineering
department we were over there in the old petroleum building uh at that time barlow was the
dean of engineering uh and uh saul wright was head of uh civil uh charlie crawford was head of
mechanical um let's see uh shepard was dean of agriculture petroleum no petroleum harold vance
was head of petroleum and shepard was head of agriculture and i don't remember i remember
mr porter was head of the math department but i don't know
who was the science dean i think pearson was dean of the graduate college followed later by trotter
but pearson i believe was the dean when i came here i worked most of the time
dealt with trotter's group over there and uh i think that's let's see street was teaching drawing
and uh i can't remember the fellow's head of arrow uh and that was that's about the one there
were no sidewalks it was all actually it was the same way it was in 1943 they had not done nothing
except tear down the wall they had never done it before and that's in today's world war and what
i came in we had you'd already gotten over the flood here but there's still a lot of veterans
and i would say that that was the toughest group to compete with i've ever ran against because all
they want to know is what's required and we'll do it because you and and your other veteran buddies
you were mentally emotionally mature ready to go to work ready to go to work you'd had experience
uh-huh and also you could separate i had a family too boy
everything was riding on it what was your what was your graduate student stipend or assistantship or
what oh it was probably about a hundred dollars a month right now uh plus the gi bill i'm not
even sure we got a hundred maybe we did i don't remember what it was but it was living in college
view we could make it but see by the time i got ready to finish i ran out of the uh i took a job
teaching i ran out of the gi bill so i had to take a job teaching and then i had to buy a house
over in college hills and i bought one on harrington street over there it cost 13 700
and that was the poorest year that i've ever experienced in my life uh we
my salary was 370 a month and uh lindsay had to get special dispensation to get me 370.
and so uh that's kind of what it was like here then now when did you switch
officially in paperwork from being a graduate student to being a faculty member 52 okay so
you're all right we're still talking about the graduate student days yeah well i finished i got
my phd in 53 but i don't know okay i took a job as instructor in 52 i think it was and then uh
i believe in uh
i guess in 53 that fall i went ahead uh i've forgotten whether i got promoted to assistant
professor maybe i went a year before i got made assistant professor looking back
now with the clear vision of hindsight what courses and what in teachers instructors
were the most important to you well uh actually we had some things back then there that are better
than they are now
and that is it we took courses outside the department a lot of them and i i took mathematics
i had luther i had baysy and then dr klippel and i and years later we worked on i'd just go over with
him and spend an hour a day every once in a while every week we'd have a meeting and prove theorems
and so on in chemistry uh jensen and dr watson i worked under murdoch phil murdoch in chemical
engineering but Watson was one of them another one that I took course over
there was pots organic chemistry and Kenny Hancock was another one that I
took course under also took a physics course and Dr.
Weeks taught it and then
after I finished my coursework I went back and took another course in kinetic
theory under Dr. Silvey which goes way back and old Dr. Silvey the first day
there were three of us in there registered for his course and he two
physics students and me and he said he said would Mr. Harlan would you like to
participate in the classroom discussion and I said well I I believe I'd like to do
that well what that amounted to were presenting one-third of that course for
audit and then I also had their one under Dr.
Weeks over there he was the
first one I took x-rays and x-rays and x-rays and x-rays and x-rays and x-rays

so Jensen was an outstanding chemistry teacher Watson was not standing

outstanding teacher he had a tremendous amount of knowledge
but he could never finish one sentence until he started another one now what

different Potts I don't remember what his first name you just have to look at
what what Department chemistry in in the chemistry he was the organic prof in
chemistry Kenny Hancock taught a good course in chemistry all right what about
what about within chemical engineering Phil Murdock I took a course under him and uh let's see you know that
I may have taken most all the courses I took under him uh I took one under GL fair he he taught
process control and I took that but we took in those years we were really taken see we didn't
teach our own mathematics in our in our department and now all these people trying to do teach
everything one department they never see the light of day outside the walls of their department did
anybody do you remember any advice that somebody gave you which later proved to be very valuable
advice to a chemical engineer oh I don't know uh I just kind of stumbled along I guess
uh I very nearly quit uh shortly after about 1955 because I went down to Exxon and at that
work one summer and they wanted me to stay with Exxon and at that time I was making five thousand
dollars a year Dr Harris was making uh 5100 a year and Dr Lindsay making 5200
a year and I was Assistant Professor professor and both of them were full and I figured well Why
should I stay here when that's all I've got that's all the future I've got so it was uh Charlie Lynch
incidentally and that old building was head of geology over there and that uh well what
what persuades you to stay I just got thinking about it that uh I don't know uh uh what had
happened was uh
I had to hurry up and get through because that one year Phil Murdoch left and Watson left
and all my committee left, so I really pushed that to get it completed.
I wasn't really sure whether I wanted to stay, I guess, in that corporate structure.
You don't have near as much freedom.
What was your dissertation topic in your area of specialization?
This was, I'd done my master's on distillation, and this one was on catalytic, study of catalysts.
And so on my committee I had Dr. Potts from biology, or Potter, Potter from biology,
and Dr.
Weeks and Dr. Watson and Phil Murdoch, I believe, were the ones on it.
And I couldn't get it arranged for the final meeting, and I went by Watson's house one,
afternoon late, and he was sitting back in the backyard with his shirt off drinking beer.
And I told him, I don't know, I'm going to be able to graduate this time
because I can't get this committee together.
Gordon said, oh, I can take care of that for you.
And he went in and called them up, and we met over in the old patrolling building that night.
He set it up, and we all met over there, and I got it over with, so I made it.
Do you remember any special questions on that final oral exam?
I don't remember.
I do.
I just remember that they asked me some question,
and I guess when you're working on some of those things,
you've got so many details in your mind, and it's some little simple something you won't see.
And they asked me that, and then they found the weakness.
And so they just, I don't remember what it was, but then they just, one after another, you know.
And that part I remember.
If you know it, let's go on to the next, you know.
But if you ever find something that you didn't know.
As you thought about it then and now look back, how did our chemical engineering department,
how did our strength compare nationally in the mid-'50s?
Oh, we were really a young department then.
And, in fact, we got down because the salaries were so poor that at one time,
we were down to just Dr. Harry's, Dr. Lindsay, and I.
And we had to get some graduate students to help us out.
So it was all we could do to even keep the doors open.
You're saying three faculty?
We got down to three faculty.
Everybody quit because salaries, they went to industry or somewhere
because salaries were so poor back in those days.
And that's about when I was about ready to throw in the towel.
But then where the real change come was when John Connolly got in there.
Salaries went up.
Ours went up.
30% a year for three or four years there.
But now let's back up.
John Calhoun came here as dean in the 50s, didn't he?
Barlow was dean when I came here.
Okay.
And then John Calhoun came next.
All right.
Do you remember any early impressions of Calhoun as the dean?
I just remember that he was much more energetic than, well, Barlow was energetic enough.
Except that I thought Calhoun was a much better individual than Barlow was.
What, did Calhoun, did he come over and visit?
Did he become acquainted with you all?
Oh, yeah.
He had us over.
He had me over to his office.
And I think he was kind of leery of old Dr. Lindsay.
And Doc had already told him, Calhoun told me, he says,
well, here's my territory and over there's yours.
Don't you get in here.
Don't you come across this.
But he did.
And Doc had asked me one time, he had me in his office talking.
I think I irritated him because he said to me, he said.
Wait, you're saying he, is this?
Calhoun.
That's Calhoun.
Okay.
He wanted to know any disincentives or negative things about Lindsay.
I said, well, even if I had some, I wouldn't tell you.
So that ended that discussion.
I may have hurt his feelings, but I was pretty loyal to him.
Old Doc.
Old Doc did the best he could with what he had.
And he didn't have much to work with.
Now, the enrollment, I'm assuming, in engineering in the 50s was going up.
Well, no.
Actually, what happened was the enrollment of everybody went down to about 1955,
which was a low point.
Oh, okay.
That was after the war was over.
And this was about in there somewhere.
Maybe even after that, they decided that they wanted to make it optional core a little bit.
And I think we went on that program for a little while and enrollment started going up.
Then we went back to compulsory core and it started going down again.
So the enrollment never, you just do everything you wanted to
and you couldn't end up with much more than two sections of about 20-some each.
And you all still had the graduate program.
Oh, yeah.
During those dry years.
And I presume that industry was generally hiring the bright youngsters when they graduated.
Yeah, we had, we had, they were,
we were always able to place them and we helped place all those people.
The only year that I couldn't get them placed was, I believe, in about 1980
when enrollment had just gone out of proportion.
And at the same time, the job market dropped completely.
So we had a real problem then.
All right.
But then Benson was after Calhoun.
After Calhoun.
Calhoun really wasn't deemed very long.
Right.
Now, he moves up to what?
Oh.
Was he assistant?
He was, went up to vice-presidential, vice-president for engineering, I think.
Okay.
Right.
When did you first meet Fred Benson?
Well, I met him before he became dean.
I knew him because we were both in a naval reserve unit together.
And he wasn't very, and we actually were taking one
of the math courses there together at one time.
He was taking one course, a lower one than I was taking.
Did he do his degree here?
Yeah, he got, he got his BS at Calhoun.
Oh.
Yeah.
He got his B.S. at Calhoun.
Oh.
Yeah.
He got his B.S.
at Kansas.
And then he got a master's several years back at here.
Okay.
As I recall.
And then he was taking some additional courses.
Describe Fred Benson as a human being, as a personality.
Well, we got along just fine.
One of the things, when I got appointed, what he did was call me in one afternoon.
He said, Charlie, I'd like for you to take over here as head of the department.
Said, now, you don't have to tell me right now.
You can wait until a little bit.
A little later and tell me if you think it over.
And so I did.
And I wasn't really sure I wanted to.
I really wanted to tell him, how about getting old Doc to take it one more year?
I'd like to do the things I'm doing a little longer.
But I decided to go ahead and take it because I thought that I could probably do more things
that I wanted to do if I were head than I could if they got somebody from the outside
and he started giving me all kinds of directions.
When was that?
What year?
That was in 19...
Right.
What...
At that point, you said things you wanted to do.
What were your goals?
Well, we had a...
I'd gone to Exxon in 55 and gotten started modeling, doing distillation on computers
and actually setting up programs to solve problems on them.
And I worked with them, consulted with them, and I had graduate students.
We'd try out new methods and we had an old 650 and that's what they had down at Exxon.
And we had an old 650 and they put it up in the old EE building.
Now this is an old key punch?
Yeah, yeah.
Punch card?
It was up in the building.
And my graduate students would go up there and use it at night.
And it had a fire escape and so they'd go up to the fire escape and run that thing all
night long.
That's what we did.
That's the way we got our time.
And we had a lot of that going on.
I'd written a book and a good many papers on it of methods that we had devised to solve
these problems.
So this was primarily...
At this point, primarily...
At this point, primarily petrochemically related.
Yeah.
Or you can do chemical either one.
It's used in both fields, not just one.
But back to Benson.
Describe him.
What did he like and not like?
How did he operate?
Well, I think although he would claim that he wanted everybody to say what they wanted
to.
He wanted to hear the right words.
And he had around him people that he knew would always back him up.
I remember I used to go in there to budget hearings.
And he'd have Ed Fenner.
Then he'd have Old Bain, Spencer.
And he'd have two or three others like that.
And he'd say something and they'd all chime in and agree.
But he and I got along pretty well because I never did...
I never did go in and ask him to solve my problems for me.
I went ahead and solved the things.
And the only time he and I got crosswise was he was pushing real hard for this Doctor of
Engineering program.
And he had all of us department heads in there one day.
And what he was wanting us to do was agree not to weaken down the B.S.
degree to where
it would not be an accredited degree and have the Doctor of Engineering be the first accredited
degree.
And I stood up against him because I told him that we could not afford to have a large
group of students coming out of here without an accredited degree.
If we're going to give a B.S.
degree, we'd better make it accredited.
And he got so mad at me that he walked out and stayed gone for about 15 minutes.
And then we finally decided we'd have it kind of optional.
If they wanted...
We'd always have the B.S.
accredited.
But if they wanted to go at an early stage somewhere over to the Doctor of Engineering,
they could.
And so we'd just leave it where whichever one won out would be the way we'd go.
And I told him we were just not big enough to fight against the whole United States on
one program like that.
They'd run us out of business.
So he and I...
And then later he says, Charlie, you can do whatever you want to.
He didn't.
But he told me many times that I had the best department in the college engineering department.
And he said, Charlie, you can do whatever you want to.
And I said, Charlie, you can do whatever you want to.
He just patted me down.
But I told him I had the best department in the college engineering.
And there was a chance at the chapter, and she'd be in it.
And I said, Well, good for you.
I thought she was going to think of me, and I got rid of it.
It was kind of bad that he wasn't here.
He thought it was anity, or something.
But I knew I was getting ready to die, and that I was going to get
out and make a living myself.
But I never really gave him any good results, and friends I met back in college, I don't
remember some of them.
Well, Chuck, he wasn't fit for engineering cars to date.
That's what I think of it.
Mitchell was a four-year-old swimmer.
and you could make a good program out of that
where you would actually do research on things
that pertain to engineering per se
more than you can on some of the directions they're going in
because they get toward the science end of it,
and then you're dealing with the physicists or the chemists and so on.
So it was a good degree.
It was just that I didn't think that we could swing it.
What did happen to it?
Well, I think they still give some of them,
but there just wasn't the demand for it.
It's just hard to sell.
All right, so there was a key decision.
That I had something to do with.
I saved him there, really.
In Benson's personality, did he laugh much?
No, he was always just in the meetings.
There was never much said.
And he got to the point pretty quickly, didn't he?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
And it was well thought out.
Anything he did was well thought out.
He was good to work for.
I didn't have a bit of trouble working for him.
I mean, he knew that I wasn't back down anymore.
I expressed my opinion.
He didn't like it, but he respected it,
and then he told me later, I think he really,
it hurt him that he couldn't handle it better than he did.
In your early years as department head,
who were your key associates?
As department heads elsewhere in engineering and anywhere else?
Oh, well, actually, in those years,
I knew all the department heads real well.
But who were the ones you worked with most?
Well, I knew Samang real well.
He and I were well acquainted.
Describe him.
Well, he was very precise and very fair,
and I had a lot of respect for him,
and he did for me.
Describe him physically.
